ocess isolation. get constraint violations. I could test this with two async flows in the same process to verify database locking works, or spawn actual subprocesses for a more realistic scenario. The minimum needed to catch the failure is an integration test, though a system test would be more representative of production.\n\nTwo async flows can genuinely test concurrent database access since the database driver multiplexes separate connections—the database itself sees two concurrent requests trying to apply the same migration. The key difference is that an integration test relies on the event loop for scheduling, while a system test uses actual OS process scheduling.\n\nFor the test plan, I should specify the integration test as the minimum requirement to catch the failure, but note that a system test would be more production-like. The real question is whether an integration test with two concurrent async operations can actually expose the issue if the code lacks proper locking—both flows could succeed in applying the migration without proper constraints.\n\nHowever, there's a distinction between simulating concurrency in-process versus actual OS-level race conditions. An integration test might miss timing edge cases that occur when separate processes read the migrations table simultaneously before attempting to acquire locks. A system test would more reliably expose these real-world race conditions, even though an integration test could theoretically catch the failure if carefully designed with appropriate delays and mocking.\n\nGiven the question's focus on catching real failures, I'm weighing the practical likelihood: System tests are more robust at 0.60 confidence, Integration tests could work but with caveats at 0.25, and the others are unlikely. The core requirement is two concurrent operations attempting the same migration with verification that only one succeeds—Integration satisfies this in principle, making it the minimum, though System provides greater confidence in practice. The real failure here is two processes both applying the same migration, creating duplicate entries in the _migrations table. To catch this, I need to simulate concurrent processes accessing the same database—something an Integration test with async flows could handle, though a System test with actual subprocesses would be more realistic. Integration is technically sufficient if I trust the database driver, but System better reflects how this would actually fail in production. I'm settling on System at 0.65 confidence since that's what would genuinely catch the issue in practice.\n\nActually, reconsidering the instructions about matching the real failure boundary—two separate instances running concurrently is fundamentally a System-level concern. While Integration could test some aspects like database locking, it can't fully replicate the \"two instances\" scenario. That pushes System to 0.75 as the true minimum, with Integration dropping to 0.10 and Workflow at 0.15.\n\nThe subprocess requirement mentioned in the instructions further confirms this—spawning separate processes is explicitly System-level work. I'm ready to structure the final output now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13714,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13714},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b5f20d2d-d8c9-40d9-ba50-37707bd811f6","uuid":"651923e2-054c-4479-8bf5-50f220c1f63e"}
